#Text=Gothenburg
#Text=Gothenburg ( Swedish : Göteborg ) is Sweden 's second largest city with 570,000 inhabitants , and about 1 million in the metropolitan area .
#Text=The city lies on Sweden 's west coast , at the outlet of the Göta river .
#Text=Gothenburg is Sweden 's largest industrial city with companies such as the Volvo Group and Volvo Cars , as well as Scandinavia 's largest port .

#Text=While the port and factories employ fewer people , the city prides itself in hosting numerous national and international sporting and music events such as Gothia Cup , Partille Cup and Way out West .
#Text=Gothenburg also has the Sweden 's largest amusement park , Liseberg .
#Text=Understand
#Text=Gothenburg is a fairly green city with parks and a large river bisecting the city .
#Text=Built after being founded by royal decree in 1621 it was modeled after Dutch city style , with plenty of canals .
#Text=Gothenburg has many humorous nicknames that allude to its canals such as " little London " , " little Amsterdam " , and " little Venice " .
#Text=Early on Gothenburg was famous for its port and trade and has prominently hosted the Swedish East-India Company .
#Text=Due to its historically industrial character Gothenburg has had strong working class associations , being known for its friendly yet brusque " goa gubbar " .
#Text=This together with its large port has given rise to the moniker " Marseille of the North " .
#Text=Today , with over 50,000 students in the city and two major universities it has a young side with plenty of bars and night-clubs .
#Text=Gothenburg has a reputation for being very friendly place , and more welcoming than Stockholm , the Swedish capital .
#Text=History
#Text=Gothenburg is at the mouth of the river Göta älv .
#Text=Lödöse , some upstream from Gothenburg was one of the largest cities in Sweden during the middle ages , and is considered a precursor of Gothenburg .
#Text=During the middle ages the mouth of Göta älv was controlled by Sweden , while Bohuslän immediately north of it was Norwegian and Halland to its immediate south was Danish .
#Text=The area thus became a tripoint of the three kingdoms .
#Text=In order to consolidate Swedish control of the area , Älvsborgs fortress was constructed near modern day Gothenburg .
#Text=Several failed attempts were also made to build a city in the area .
#Text=The modern city of Gothenburg was built in 1621 by the Swedish king Gustav II Adolf .
#Text=During the 17th century Sweden conquered Bohuslän and Halland , thus making Gothenburg the center of an expanded western Sweden .
#Text=During this era the older Danish Älvsborg fortress was demolished .
#Text=It was replaced by a new castle , ingeniously called New Älvsborg fortress , on an island in the mouth of the river .
#Text=Gothenburg eventually became a major gateway into Sweden , and one of the busiest ports in the Nordic countries .
#Text=As the largest port in Sweden Gothenburg became the seat of the Swedish East India Company in the 18th century , and a hub for American emigration in the 19th century .
#Text=During this era the city also became heavily industrialized , particularly as a center for the Swedish shipbuilding industry .

#Text=Its large port , strong trade community and proximity to Marstrand meant the city had a large Jewish and international community , with the first Jewish association forming before that of Stockholm .
#Text=With rising competition from foreign ship yards in the 1900s , many of the dry docks closed down in the 1970s .
#Text=Much of the inner harbor area has changed from industrial ship building to high technology and education , representative of the general change in the city .
#Text=Today Gothenburg has international sporting events , concerts , and conventions .
#Text=Being an industrial center , Gothenburg has been politically dominated by the left-wing Social Democrats for many years .
#Text=In the 1960s with Sweden investing heavily in affordable housing with Miljonprogrammet large parts of the working class town was demolished .

#Text=Much like parts of Södermalm in Stockholm , Masthugget was an entire district comprised nearly exclusively of small red-painted wooden houses , some of which had stone-laid ground floors , so called Landhövdingehus .
#Text=Today such houses can only be found at Gathenhielmska kulturreservatet by Stigbergstorget in Majorna , as well as on some of the islands in the Gothenburg archipelago .
#Text=Gothenburg is famous for its Landshövdingehus of which more upscale housing remains in Haga , Gårda and Majorna .
#Text=People

#Text=The working-class history is easily visible , for example in the harbor area , especially on the northern riverfront of Hisingen and north of the city center on the southern riverfront in Gullbergsvass .
#Text=Before the 1970s there were few fashion houses or posher cafeterias , but that has changed .
#Text=The Gothenburg dialect is associated with cheerfulness and witty , if pun-laden humour , with many humorists classically from Gothenburg , often of the " goa gubbar " ( lit .
#Text=" good guys " ) stereotype , working class and somewhat fat .
#Text=The connection to Britain has been said to be behind the high frequency of the male given name Glenn .
#Text=Like Marseille in France there is some animosity towards the capital , with those who move there sometimes being called " traitors " .
#Text=Climate
#Text=Like most of southern and coastal Sweden , the city is best visited during springtime as well as in the summer .
#Text=The climate is temperate with mild winters and warm , but not hot summers .
#Text=Because it is located on the west coast by the sea the climate is milder and rainier in the winter than Stockholm , but comparable to Copenhagen .
#Text=Snow is not a given in winter , for real Scandinavian winter , visit Dalarna or Norrland .
#Text=In other words , May to September tend to have the most comfortable weather .
#Text=From Midsummer to the end of July , many inhabitants leave the city , and some venues close for summer , making the city more dominated by tourists .
#Text=Tourist information
#Text=Kungsportsplatsen Tourist Office , Kungsportsplatsen 2 ( About ten minutes walk from Nordstan ) , ☏ +46313684200 , ✉ turistinfo@goteborg.com .
#Text=Nordstan Tourist Office , Nordstadstorget ( Next to the central train station ) , ☏ +46313684200 , ✉ turistinfo@goteborg.com .
#Text=Gothenburg offers the Gothenburg City Card , which allows entry into many tourist attractions , grand houses , museums as well as offering free travel on trams and buses and free parking .

#Text=Among attractions covered are Ringlinien vintage train , admission to Liseberg , Universeum , free travel with Paddan boat , boat trip to New Älvsborg Fortress , guided tour by bus , Museum of World Culture , Gothenburg Natural History Museum , Gothenburg City Museum , Gothenburg Art Museum , Röhsska Museum , Maritime Museum Aquarium , Medical History Museum , the Sports Museum , Maritiman , Casino Cosmopol , Gothenburgs utkiken , Guided tour of Gunnebo House , the Garden Society of Gothenburg , Greenhouses in the Botanical Garden , Röda Sten , Stinsen Sightseeing , Aeroseum , Volvo Museum , Mölndals Museum .
#Text=This card is available to people 's mobile phones , making it not only cost-effective and convenient .
#Text=In case official tourist information is unavailable , Gothenburgers are usually more than willing to help .
